In her public life, Heather Morgan seems to have been the cringiest imagina=
ble=C2=A0sort of crypto-adjacent hustle-bro. Here is a nightmarish YouTube =
video of her rapping. (=E2=80=9CThis song is for the entrepreneurs,=E2=80=
=9D it begins.) Here is an even more nightmarish TikTok video of her rappin=
g.=C2=A0Here is the program for a talk she gave at a tech salon about =E2=
=80=9CHow to Social Engineer Your Way Into Anything=E2=80=9D; here are some=
 slides. Here is, and I cannot stress this enough, her Forbes contributor p=
age.In her private life=C2=A0she allegedly conspired to launder=C2=A0$4.5 b=
illion of Bitcoin stolen from a crypto exchange?The U.S. seized about $3.6 =
billion in Bitcoin stolen during a 2016 hack of the Bitfinex currency excha=
nge -- the largest financial seizure ever -- and arrested two people, the J=
ustice Department said.=C2=A0Ilya Lichtenstein and his wife, Heather Morgan=
, were detained Tuesday morning and are scheduled to appear at federal cour=
t in Manhattan in the afternoon, the Justice Department said in a statement=
. The two -- who appear to have had colorful social media accounts ahead of=
 their arrests -- allegedly conspired to launder 119,754 Bitcoin stolen aft=
er a hacker breached Bitfinex=E2=80=99s systems. ...Bitfinex is the exchang=
e affiliated with the world=E2=80=99s biggest stablecoin, Tether. At the ti=
me of the hack, the digital currency haul was estimated at about $71 millio=
n, the Justice Department said. The department said the total value of stol=
en Bitcoin is now worth about $4.5 billion. =E2=80=A6Lichtenstein, 34, and =
Morgan, 31, also funneled the money through AlphaBay Marketplace, which was=
 shut down in 2017, to hide their transactions. Some of the money was cashe=
d out through Bitcoin ATMs. Some was used to buy NFTs and gold. They even u=
sed the money to buy a Walmart gift card.What a cover story. I am certainly=
 not telling you to steal $4.5 billion of Bitcoin from=C2=A0a crypto exchan=
ge and launder it through the financial system. That is frowned upon, it is=
 not nice=C2=A0to the people whose crypto was stolen, and you will probably=
 go to prison. It=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0good. It is, however =E2=80=A6=C2=A0lo=
ok I am sorry it is=C2=A0cool. Like if I met the person who did that I woul=
d be=C2=A0impressed, by the boldness, and by the fact that she has $4.5=C2=
=A0billion. And when I think about the person who did that, the words that =
do not come to mind are=C2=A0=E2=80=9CForbes rapper.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Lichtens=
tein allegedly did more of the laundering but much less of the rapping; he =
seems to have been into more standard crypto-guy stuff:Lichtenstein, who we=
nt by the nickname =E2=80=9CDutch,=E2=80=9D described himself as an angel i=
nvestor in technology companies, as well as an adviser to multiple startups=
, according to a public LinkedIn profile. A Twitter account with his name a=
lso posted frequently, weighing in on topics such as cryptocurrency trends,=
 the technology sector and the evolution of NFTs.=C2=A0Here are the Justice=
 Department press release and the criminal complaint. In August 2016, a hac=
ker =E2=80=94=C2=A0there is no allegation that it was Lichtenstein or Morga=
n, though why=C2=A0would=C2=A0the hacker hand the loot over to them?[1] =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0stole =E2=80=9Capproximately 119,754 BTC=E2=80=9D from the wall=
et of the Bitfinex crypto exchange, worth about $71 million at the time of =
the hack, about $4.5 billion at the time the Justice Department wrote the c=
omplaint last week,=C2=A0and about $5.3 billion as of this morning. (=E2=80=
=9CThe trading value of BTC fluctuates over time, depending on market deman=
d,=E2=80=9D the complaint says in a dry footnote.) The Justice Department=
=C2=A0recovered 94,636 of those Bitcoins (worth $57 million in August 2016,=
 $3.6 billion in the complaint and about $4.2 billion today), which it will=
  give back: =E2=80=9CIn a briefing for reporters, Justice Department offic=
ials said they plan to establish a court process for victims to reclaim the=
 stolen Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D[2]Lichtenstein and=C2=A0Morgan are charged with t=
rying to launder the money. Classically, the idea of money laundering is th=
at, when you do crimes, it is often hard to=C2=A0spend=C2=A0your ill-gotten=
 loot. If you steal a sack of cash from a bank and try to buy a car with it=
, people will get suspicious. This is particularly true of stolen=C2=A0Bitc=
oins: Spending Bitcoins mostly requires converting them into dollars (or eu=
ros, or gold, or non-fungible tokens, or something), which mostly requires =
going through a cryptocurrency exchange. So you want to take your suspiciou=
s loot and filter it through the legitimate financial system until it comes=
 out in a respectable bank account that you can use to buy stuff.Government=
s want to prevent this, and so regulated financial institutions =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0especially banks, but in recent years also especially legitimate cryp=
tocurrency exchanges =E2=80=94=C2=A0have know-your-customer/anti-money-laun=
dering=C2=A0(KYC/AML) compliance programs where, if you walk into a bank wi=
th a large=C2=A0sack of cash and say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d like to deposit t=
his please,=E2=80=9D they ask you questions like =E2=80=9Cwho are you=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9Cwhere did you get this money.=E2=80=9D If the answer is =
=E2=80=9CI stole it from a crypto exchange=E2=80=9D they will call the cops=
, so you have to lie=C2=A0(which is a crime), and also they might check (so=
 you might get caught).=C2=A0Here is how the Justice Department summarizes =
the laundering here:The criminal complaint alleges that Lichtenstein and Mo=
rgan employed numerous sophisticated laundering techniques, including using=
 fictitious identities to set up online accounts; utilizing computer progra=
ms to automate transactions, a laundering technique that allows for many tr=
ansactions to take place in a short period of time; depositing the stolen f=
unds into accounts at a variety of virtual currency exchanges and darknet m=
arkets and then withdrawing the funds, which obfuscates the trail of the tr=
ansaction history by breaking up the fund flow; converting bitcoin to other=
 forms of virtual currency, including anonymity-enhanced virtual currency (=
AEC), in a practice known as =E2=80=9Cchain hopping=E2=80=9D; and using U.S=
.-based business accounts to legitimize their banking activity.=E2=80=9CIn =
a methodical and calculated scheme, the defendants allegedly laundered and =
disguised their vast fortune,=E2=80=9D said Chief Jim Lee of IRS-Criminal I=
nvestigation (IRS-CI).But if you read the complaint, what is striking is ho=
w little of the money actually got laundered. Certainly a lot of effort see=
ms to have gone into laundering. But the thing is that if you are a TikTok =
rapper and you walk into a bank and say =E2=80=9Chello I=E2=80=99d like to =
open an account in which to deposit the proceeds of my TikTok rapping=E2=80=
=9D and the bank says =E2=80=9Csure okay=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=9Chere=
 is my first deposit of $4.5 billion=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=99ll be in jail tha=
