U1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjI=
wMjA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBad75fab8" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">conspired to launder=C2=A0$4.5 billion of Bitcoin stolen from a crypt=
o exchange</a>?</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The U.S. seized=
 about $3.6 billion in Bitcoin stolen during a 2016 hack of the Bitfinex cu=
rrency exchange -- the largest financial seizure ever -- and arrested two p=
eople, the Justice Department said.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=
lya Lichtenstein and his wife, Heather Morgan, were detained Tuesday mornin=
g and are scheduled to appear at federal court in Manhattan in the afternoo=
n, the Justice Department said in a statement. The two -- who appear to hav=
e had colorful social media accounts ahead of their arrests -- allegedly co=
nspired to launder 119,754 Bitcoin stolen after a hacker breached Bitfinex=
=E2=80=99s systems. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bitfinex is the exc=
hange affiliated with the world=E2=80=99s biggest stablecoin, Tether. At th=
e time of the hack, the digital currency haul was estimated at about $71 mi=
llion, the Justice Department said. The department said the total value of =
stolen Bitcoin is now worth about $4.5 billion. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Lichtenstein, 34, and Morgan, 31, also funneled the money th=
rough AlphaBay Marketplace, which was shut down in 2017, to hide their tran=
sactions. Some of the money was cashed out through Bitcoin ATMs. Some was u=
sed to buy NFTs and gold. They even used the money to buy a Walmart gift ca=
rd.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What a cover story. I am c=
ertainly not telling you to steal $4.5 billion of Bitcoin from=C2=A0a crypt=
o exchange and launder it through the financial system. That is frowned upo=
n, it is not nice=C2=A0to the people whose crypto was stolen, and you will =
probably go to prison. It=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0<em>good</em>. It is, however =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0look I am sorry it is=C2=A0<em>cool</em>. Like if I met the =
person who did that I would be=C2=A0<em>impressed</em>, by the boldness, an=
d by the fact that she has $4.5=C2=A0billion. And when I think about the pe=
rson who did that, the words that do not come to mind are=C2=A0=E2=80=9CFor=
bes rapper.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lichtenstein all=
egedly did more of the laundering but much less of the rapping; he seems to=
 have been into more standard crypto-guy stuff:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Lichtenstein, who went by the nickname =E2=80=9CDutch,=E2=
=80=9D described himself as an angel investor in technology companies, as w=
ell as an adviser to multiple startups, according to a public LinkedIn prof=
ile. A Twitter account with his name also posted frequently, weighing in on=
 topics such as cryptocurrency trends, the technology sector and the evolut=
ion of NFTs.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are th=
e Justice Department <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/26652347.266610/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3Yvb3BhL3ByL3R3by1hcnJlc3Rl=
ZC1hbGxlZ2VkLWNvbnNwaXJhY3ktbGF1bmRlci00NS1iaWxsaW9uLXN0b2xlbi1jcnlwdG9jdXJ=
yZW5jeQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3cb486e8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">press release</a> and th=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26652347.266610/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3Yvb3BhL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvZmlsZS8xNDcwMjExL2R=
vd25sb2Fk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB68679281" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">criminal complaint</a>=
. In August 2016, a hacker =E2=80=94=C2=A0there is no allegation that it wa=
s Lichtenstein or Morgan, though why=C2=A0would<em>=C2=A0</em>the hacker ha=
nd the loot over to them?[1] =E2=80=94=C2=A0stole =E2=80=9Capproximately 11=
9,754 BTC=E2=80=9D from the wallet of the Bitfinex crypto exchange, worth a=
bout $71 million at the time of the hack, about $4.5 billion at the time th=
e Justice Department wrote the complaint last week,=C2=A0and about $5.3 bil=
lion as of this morning. (=E2=80=9CThe trading value of BTC fluctuates over=
 time, depending on market demand,=E2=80=9D the complaint says in a dry foo=
tnote.) The Justice Department=C2=A0recovered 94,636 of those Bitcoins (wor=
th $57 million in August 2016, $3.6 billion in the complaint and about $4.2=
 billion today), which it will <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/26652347.266610/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMDgvZG9qLXNlaXplcy0zLTYtYmlsbGlvbi1pbi1iaXRjb2luLXN0b2xlb=
i1pbi0yMDE2LWJpdGZpbmV4LWhhY2s_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIwOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21l=
ZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjA5JnV0bV9jYW1=
wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCad75fab8" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> give back=
</a>: =E2=80=9CIn a briefing for reporters, Justice Department officials sa=
id they plan to establish a court process for victims to reclaim the stolen=
 Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lichtenstein and=C2=
=A0Morgan are charged with trying to launder the money. Classically, the id=
ea of money laundering is that, when you do crimes, it is often hard to=C2=
=A0<em>spend=C2=A0</em>your ill-gotten loot. If you steal a sack of cash fr=
om a bank and try to buy a car with it, people will get suspicious. This is=
 particularly true of stolen=C2=A0<em>Bitcoins</em>: Spending Bitcoins most=
ly requires converting them into dollars (or euros, or gold, or non-fungibl=
e tokens, or something), which mostly requires going through a cryptocurren=
cy exchange. So you want to take your suspicious loot and filter it through=
 the legitimate financial system until it comes out in a respectable bank a=
ccount that you can use to buy stuff.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gover=
nments want to prevent this, and so regulated financial institutions =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0especially banks, but in recent years also especially legitimate c=
ryptocurrency exchanges =E2=80=94=C2=A0have know-your-customer/anti-money-l=
aundering=C2=A0(KYC/AML) compliance programs where, if you walk into a bank=
 with a large=C2=A0sack of cash and say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d like to deposi=
t this please,=E2=80=9D they ask you questions like =E2=80=9Cwho are you=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwhere did you get this money.=E2=80=9D If the answer is=
 =E2=80=9CI stole it from a crypto exchange=E2=80=9D they will call the cop=
s, so you have to lie=C2=A0(which is a crime), and also they might check (s=
o you might get caught).=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is how =
the Justice Department summarizes the laundering here:</p><blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The criminal complaint alleges that Lichtenstein an=
d Morgan employed numerous sophisticated laundering techniques, including u=
sing fictitious identities to set up online accounts; utilizing computer pr=
ograms to automate transactions, a laundering technique that allows for man=
y transactions to take place in a short period of time; depositing the stol=
en funds into accounts at a variety of virtual currency exchanges and darkn=
et markets and then withdrawing the funds, which obfuscates the trail of th=
e transaction history by breaking up the fund flow; converting bitcoin to o=
ther forms of virtual currency, including anonymity-enhanced virtual curren=
cy (AEC), in a practice known as =E2=80=9Cchain hopping=E2=80=9D; and using=
 U.S.-based business accounts to legitimize their banking activity.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIn a methodical and calculated scheme, th=
e defendants allegedly laundered and disguised their vast fortune,=E2=80=9D=
 said Chief Jim Lee of IRS-Criminal Investigation (IRS-CI).</p></blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if you read the complaint, what is striki=
ng is how little of the money actually got laundered. Certainly a lot of ef=
fort seems to have gone into laundering. But the thing is that if you are a=
 TikTok rapper and you walk into a bank and say =E2=80=9Chello I=E2=80=99d =
like to open an account in which to deposit the proceeds of my TikTok rappi=
ng=E2=80=9D and the bank says =E2=80=9Csure okay=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=
=80=9Chere is my first deposit of $4.5 billion=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=99ll be i=
n jail that afternoon. You gotta launder slow.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">And so about 80% of the 119,754 Bitcoin stolen from Bitfinex =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the $3.6 billion the government recovered =E2=80=94 stayed put in the=
 same Bitcoin wallet that was used in the hack. The complaint summarizes th=
e hack (=E2=80=9CVictim VCE,=E2=80=9D for =E2=80=9Cvirtual currency exchang=
e,=E2=80=9D is Bitfinex):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In or=
 around August 2016, a hacker breached Victim VCE=E2=80=99s=C2=A0security s=
ystems and infiltrated its infrastructure. While inside Victim VCE=E2=80=99=
s network, the hacker was able to initiate over 2,000 unauthorized BTC tran=
sactions, in which approximately 119,754 BTC was transferred from Victim VC=
E=E2=80=99s wallets=C2=A0to an outside wallet (Wallet 1CGA4s ).=C2=A0</p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWallet 1CGa4s=E2=80=9D is =
the name given to the set of Bitcoin blockchain addresses=C2=A0where the ha=
cker allegedly=C2=A0received transfers of the Bitfinex funds. Some money le=
ft that wallet to be laundered:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>U.S. authorities traced the stolen funds on the BTC blockchain.=C2=A0As de=
tailed below, beginning in or around January 2017, a portion of the stolen =
BTC moved out of Wallet 1CGA4s in a series of small, complex transactions a=
cross multiple accounts and platforms. This shuffling, which created a volu=
minous number of transactions, appeared to be designed to conceal the path =
of the stolen BTC, making it difficult for law enforcement to trace the fun=
ds.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But most of the money stay=
ed right where it was from 2016 until the government seized it last week:</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The 2017 transfers notwithstandi=
ng, the majority of the stolen funds remained in Wallet 1CGA4s from August =
2016 until January 31, 2022. On January 31, 2022, law enforcement gained ac=
cess to Wallet 1CGA4s by decrypting a file saved to LICHTENSTEIN=E2=80=99s =
cloud storage account,=C2=A0which had been obtained pursuant to a search wa=
rrant. The file contained a list of 2,000 virtual currency addresses, along=
 with corresponding private keys.=C2=A0Blockchain analysis confirmed that a=
lmost all=C2=A0of those addresses were directly linked to the hack. Between=
 January 31, 2022, and February 1, 2022, law enforcement obtained approval =
to execute a lawful seizure supported by probable cause under exigent circu=
mstances and used the private keys from LICHTENSTEIN=E2=80=99s file to seiz=
e Wallet 1CGA4=E2=80=99s remaining balance of approximately 94,636 BTC, wor=
th $3.629 billion. On February 2, 2022, the government requested, and on Fe=
bruary 4, 2022, a court issued a seizure warrant authorizing the seizure of=
 those funds. Those funds remain secured in the U.S. Government=E2=80=99s p=
ossession.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ah. I <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26652347.266610/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMDYvbm9ib2R5LXdhbnRzLX=
RvLW1pc3BsYWNlLXRoZWlyLWNyeXB0bz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjA5MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fb=
WVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAyMDkmdXRtX2Nh=
bXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe83a67a0" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> often s=
ay</a> around here that the most important challenge for institutional inve=
stors looking to own Bitcoin is remembering their passwords. Apparently thi=
s is also a challenge for hackers looking to steal Bitcoin, or launderers l=
ooking to launder it. So many private keys to remember! You can etch them o=
n metal plates and bury them in your backyard, but that isn=E2=80=99t very =
useful for a high-volume laundering business. You can write them down in a =
notebook, but I hypothesize that you have bad handwriting and are more comf=
ortable with computers, plus what if you lose the notebook. You can type th=
em in a file on your computer and save it, but you are computer-savvy enoug=
h to know that you should back up your files to the cloud. (Or: You can wri=
te them in your phone=E2=80=99s notes app, which automatically saves=C2=A0t=
o the cloud?) And then guess what Apple or Amazon or Google has your list o=
f 2,000 private keys for the billions of dollars of Bitcoin you allegedly s=
tole. And then guess what so does the FBI. All very understandable, and yet=
: oops! Decentralization!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a chart o=
f some of the alleged laundering in 2017:</p><!--[if mso]>
