<![endif]--><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The font is small, but the point I=
 want to make here is that the number in the top box has a comma and the nu=
mbers in the lower boxes have decimal points. In the top box, 119,754 Bitco=
in=C2=A0was stolen from Bitfinex and moved to Wallet 1CGA4s. In the remaini=
ng boxes, other amounts of Bitcoin were moved to various accounts at AlphaB=
ay (=E2=80=9Cone of the largest darknet markets,=E2=80=9D which was=C2=A0<a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26652347.266610/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuZmJpLmdvdi9uZXdzL3N0b3JpZXMvYWxwaGFiYXktdGFrZWRvd24/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBc5a03759" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">shut down in 2017</a>)=C2=A0and then to var=
ious accounts at another crypto exchange (=E2=80=9CVCE 1=E2=80=9D), but the=
 numbers are all like 6.757 Bitcoin, or 2.228, or 11.986. The theft was lar=
ge, but the laundering transactions were small. Also they didn=E2=80=99t wo=
rk:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The relevant VCE 1 accounts=
 were registered in the names of third parties unrelated to LICHTENSTEIN an=
d MORGAN. VCE 1 was unable to verify the identities of any of the listed ac=
count owners. Specifically, in February and March 2017, VCE 1=E2=80=99s emp=
loyees requested that the registered accountholders for seven of the accoun=
ts provide additional identifying information to verify their account owner=
ship. VCE 1 did not receive a response to these requests. As a result, VCE =
1 froze=C2=A0the accounts. In total, the accounts contained over $186,000 U=
.S. dollars=E2=80=99 worth of virtual currency at the time, in or around Ap=
ril 2017.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They allegedly set u=
p seven accounts at AlphaBay and six accounts at a legit crypto exchange to=
 withdraw $186,000 of their millions, and it got frozen anyway. Oh well.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They did have some luck, though; some of the =
Bitcoins that moved through AlphaBay and VCE 1 got out before the freeze an=
d ended up in their accounts at another exchange (=E2=80=9CVCE 5=E2=80=9D),=
 where they were allegedly turned into untraceable portable property. Still=
, you can identify some tradecraft flaws here:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Records from VCE 5 showed that Lichtenstein=E2=80=99s VCE 5=
 Account was opened on or about January 13, 2015, in his name and using his=
 address at the time in San Francisco. The account was verified with photog=
raphs of LICHTENSTEIN=E2=80=99s California driver=E2=80=99s license and a s=
elfie-style photograph. The account was registered to an email address cont=
aining LICHTENSTEIN=E2=80=99s first name (=E2=80=9CLichtenstein Email 1=E2=
=80=9D). Search warrants for the contents of the Lichtenstein Email 1 accou=
nt confirmed that LICHTENSTEIN controlled the account, as well as a related=
 account which included LICHTENSTEIN=E2=80=99s nickname (=E2=80=9CLichtenst=
ein Email 2=E2=80=9D)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lichtenstein=E2=80=99=
s VCE 5 Account was used to purchase gold from a precious metals dealer thr=
ough a U.S.-based virtual currency payment service provider (=E2=80=9CBTC P=
SP 1=E2=80=9D).=C2=A0In conducting the transaction, LICHTENSTEIN provided h=
is true home address for shipment.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">In a sense, turning stolen Bitcoins into physical gold is a money-laun=
dering success. In another sense, giving your driver=E2=80=99s license to=
=C2=A0a regulated financial institution so that it can ship the gold to you=
r home address is, in hindsight,=C2=A0not.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
There were other successes. Some of the Bitcoins went into yet another exch=
ange, =E2=80=9CVCE 7,=E2=80=9D where Lichtenstein and Morgan each opened pe=
rsonal accounts and where Morgan opened an account for her business, which =
is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26652347.266610=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9zYWxlc2ZvbGsuY29tLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB69c3d4d8" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
called SalesFolk</a> (=E2=80=9Cthe first company to specialize in cold emai=
l copywriting=E2=80=9D). From there, the Bitcoins were turned into money in=
 the bank that could presumably be spent:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">In total, their three accounts at VCE 7 received around $2.9 mil=
lion worth of BTC for the approximate period of March 1, 2017, to October 2=
4, 2021, all after the hack of Victim VCE. Nearly all of the BTC received w=
as converted to fiat currency and withdrawn to U.S. financial institution (=
USFI)=C2=A0accounts held by MORGAN and LICHTENSTEIN.</p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is a tiny sliver of the $4.5=C2=A0billion hacki=
ng proceeds but still a respectable income. But VCE 7 is a regulated financ=
ial institution, so it asked them standard KYC/AML questions.=C2=A0The Just=
ice Department objects to Lichtenstein=E2=80=99s and Morgan's answers:</p><=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Specifically, on February 27, 2017,=
 LICHTENSTEIN wrote the following to representatives from VCE 7: =E2=80=9CH=
i, I=E2=80=99m a tech entrepreneur and [BTC] early adopter since acquiring =
my first BTC in 2011. I=E2=80=99m looking to diversify a bit ahead of the E=
TF decision and sell about 100BTC. Please let me know the next steps to mov=
e forward. All trades I would execute are from my own personal funds, the L=
LC is simply there to manage my trading assets.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, I am sure they get that 20 times a day a=
nd it=E2=80=99s usually true? Meanwhile:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">MORGAN represented via email to VCE 7 that she would be using her=
 accounts at VCE 7 to receive funds from her business clients and also to t=
ransact with her own virtual currency. MORGAN claimed that the source of di=
gital assets that would be deposited in her institutional account would be =
virtual currency that she had received in 2014 and 2015 from LICHTENSTEIN. =
This claim is belied by the blockchain, which shows that her virtual curren=
cy accounts received the bulk of deposits from the above-referenced account=
s at VCE 4 and received none from identifiable business clients.=C2=A0</p><=
/blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes there is an important money-la=
undering tip here: If you come to a bank with a sack of cash and say =E2=80=
=9CI, uh, inherited this from my grandmother, she kept cash in sacks,=E2=80=
=9D that is somewhat hard for the authorities to check. If you come to a cr=
ypto exchange with a sack of Bitcoins and say =E2=80=9CI got these cheap in=
 2014,=E2=80=9D that is easier to check. Permanent immutable public ledger =
on the blockchain! Also:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Jul=
y 1, 2019, MORGAN stated that SalesFolk was not a financial institution, an=
d so she does not manage her customers=E2=80=99 money in any way. =E2=80=9C=
[SalesFolk=E2=80=99s customers are] just B2B companies buying software and/=
or sales/email marketing consulting services from us, typically around $850=
0 or less per contract/invoice, so we haven=E2=80=99t been doing any KYC on=
 them.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On July 2, 2019, a represen=
tative from VCE 7 asked MORGAN some follow-up questions about how MORGAN ca=
me to own the digital assets that would be deposited into her new instituti=
onal account. Morgan stated, =E2=80=9CMy boyfriend (now husband) gifted me =
cryptocurrency over several years (2014, 2015,), [sic] which have appreciat=
ed. I have been keeping them in cold storage.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">On January 15, 2020, a representative from VCE 7 reached out to=
 MORGAN for monthly funding amounts, trading volume, and transactional acti=
vity for the account going forward. MORGAN replied that she anticipated tha=
t monthly funding activity would be approximately =E2=80=9C10-30K USD=E2=80=
=9D and the trading volume would be =E2=80=9C10-20k on average.=E2=80=9D</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As previously stated, although MORGAN advised=
 representatives from VCE 7 that SalesFolk received virtual currency from s=
ome of her customers, investigators were not able to locate anything on the=
 SalesFolk website referencing accepting or dealing with cryptocurrency</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Allegedly setting up a small busi=
ness to launder =E2=80=9C10-30K USD=E2=80=9D a month of stolen Bitcoins is=
=C2=A0<em>something</em>, it will definitely subsidize a TikTok rap career,=
 but it will not buy you an island.=C2=A0The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/26652347.266610/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRp=
Y2xlcy9qdXN0aWNlLWRlcGFydG1lbnQtc2F5cy1pdC1zZWl6ZWQtMy02LWJpbGxpb24taW4tc3R=
vbGVuLWNyeXB0b2N1cnJlbmN5LWV4Y2hhbmdlLWhhY2stMTE2NDQzMzkzODE/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBf8570d4d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</p><blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A friend of Ms. Morgan said the couple, whi=
le planning to buy a $2 million apartment in New York, didn=E2=80=99t live =
a lavish lifestyle and weren=E2=80=99t splashy spenders. The friend said th=
eir wedding in November was modest and the couple said they often used air =
miles to fly.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These people are=
 charged with money-laundering conspiracy, but their real tragedy is that t=
hey allegedly did a lot of conspiring without a whole lot of=C2=A0<em>laund=
ering</em>. They were allegedly billionaires in ill-gotten Bitcoin, and the=
y couldn=E2=80=99t spend it.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said, =
I must admit that $4.5 billion minus $3.6 billion is $900 million. Actually=
 it=E2=80=99s $1.1 billion, due to the Bitcoin's volatility: They allegedly=
 took 119,754 Bitcoins=C2=A0from Bitfinex, and the Justice Department recov=
ered 94,636 Bitcoins from their main starting wallet, meaning that about 25=
,000 Bitcoins =E2=80=94=C2=A0worth about $1.1 billion at today=E2=80=99s pr=
ice =E2=80=94=C2=A0has left that wallet and eluded the Justice Department. =
From the complaint I suspect that some of that is in accessible accounts th=
at the Justice Department still plans to seize, and I suspect that a lot=C2=
=A0of it was spent back when Bitcoin was worth a lot less than it is today.=
 There is no strong implication that they successfully laundered and squirr=
eled away hundreds of millions of dollars, safe from Justice Department sei=
zure. But it=E2=80=99s not completely ruled out either. =E2=80=9CThe couple=
 is also believed to have access to $330 million in bitcoin that the federa=
l government hasn=E2=80=99t located,=E2=80=9D prosecutors <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26652347.266610/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3N=
qLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9qdXN0aWNlLWRlcGFydG1lbnQtc2F5cy1pdC1zZWl6ZWQtMy02LWJpbG=
xpb24taW4tc3RvbGVuLWNyeXB0b2N1cnJlbmN5LWV4Y2hhbmdlLWhhY2stMTE2NDQzMzkzODE/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCf8570d4d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">said at a bail hearing</a>. Thoug=
h they still have to launder that I guess.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
There is a strange debate about crypto and money laundering. Crypto skeptic=
s will often say =E2=80=9CBitcoin is mostly useful for money laundering=E2=
=80=9D; crypto proponents will occasionally say =E2=80=9Cwhat of it, money =
laundering is fine, freedom, man,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0but mostly they will instea=
d say =E2=80=9Cno, Bitcoin is useless for money laundering because it creat=
es a permanent public record of all transactions and why would you want to =
launder money that way.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might =
think that a federal criminal indictment for $4.5 billion of Bitcoin money =
laundering would be vindication of the =E2=80=9CBitcoin is for money launde=
rers=E2=80=9D side, but I want to tell you: No it is not! What allegedly ha=
ppened here is that hackers=C2=A0<em>stole=C2=A0</em>$4.5 billion of Bitcoi=
n from a crypto exchange (and stealing from exchanges absolutely=C2=A0<em>i=
s=C2=A0</em>a major function of crypto), and then they had=C2=A0<em>a horri=
ble</em> time laundering it. They managed to extract only a relatively smal=
l portion of the money=C2=A0for actual spending,=C2=A0and each time they go=
t money out=C2=A0the feds were able to trace it from the hack all the way t=
o legitimate accounts with their names on it. The laundering efforts were s=
mall-scale, and they are=C2=A0also=C2=A0<em>how they got caught</em>.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you rob a bank and steal a sack of money and =
the bills are sequentially numbered and a dye pack explodes in the sack and=
 you=C2=A0drive directly to another bank and hand them the dye-stained sack=
 and say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d like to make a deposit please=E2=80=9D you wi=
ll <em>totally </em>get arrested, and you will probably get charged with=C2=
=A0<em>money laundering</em>, but in no meaningful sense did you launder th=
e money. It still has the dye on it! That happened here.</p><table class=3D=
