</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two good times to quit your =
job on Wall Street: when business is bad, and when business is good. When b=
usiness is bad, your job is very unpleasant =E2=80=94=C2=A0you are not doin=
g deals, but you=E2=80=99re spending a lot of time on grim targeting exerci=
ses and infighting =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it doesn=E2=80=99t pay particularly w=
ell. So you can afford to go do something else, because it wouldn=E2=80=99t=
 be that big a pay cut from your Wall Street job anyway, and it would be mo=
re pleasant.=C2=A0When business is=C2=A0good, your job is exciting but you =
work too hard and get burned out, and then you get a giant bonus at the end=
 of the year. So you can afford to go do something else, because you can pa=
y off your mortgage with that bonus and the pay cut is less daunting.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Business is good now, and it=E2=80=99s bonus sea=
son, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26652347.2666=
